            "creation_date": 1410504487,
            "body": "<p>You would call then exactly as if they weren't in a jar-file but in the same project.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>org.math.DMAS.add(3,4);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 25802373,
            "question_id": 25802310
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/pdX5X.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 4356045,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3554638,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3554638/zohaib",
                "reputation": 53,
                "display_name": "Zohaib"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1410515136,
            "creation_date": 1410515136,
            "body": "<p>Assuming that you have created and added the JAR correctly. It is not different from the scenario where you can call these functions from a package containing DMAS.java with in your project \"AdvancedCalculator\"  <br>\nThere are two ways: <br><\/p>\n\n<pre><code>import org.math.DMAS;\n// with in the main function of class of \"AdvancedCalculator\" invoke a function like\nDMAS.add(arg1,arg2);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Or you can use this line to invoke a function, without importing DMAS.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>org.math.DMAS.add(arg1,arg2);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>To check the validity of created JAR, you can Expand it from Referenced Libraries and check if DMAS.class exists and also compare the function's definition in JAR with the function call. Make sure you are interfacing correctly.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 25805358,
            "question_id": 25802310
        },
